   <div class="maketitle">



<h2 class="titleHead">A 45-year time series of dune mobility indicating
constant wind velocity over the central Sahara</h2>
               <div class="author" ><span 
class="cmr-12x-x-120">Pieter Vermeesch</span><span 
class="cmr-10"><sup>1</sup></span><span 
class="cmsy-10">*</span> <span 
class="cmr-12x-x-120">and Sebastien Leprince</span><span 
class="cmr-10"><sup>2</sup></span><br />
<br />                <span 
class="cmr-8"><sup>1</sup></span>Birkbeck, University of London, United Kingdom
<br />           <span 
class="cmr-8"><sup>2</sup></span>California Institute of Technology, Pasadena, United States
<br />
<br /><span 
class="cmsy-8">*</span>To whom correspondence should be addressed; E-mail: <span class="obeylines-h"><span class="verb"><span 
class="cmtt-12">p.vermeesch [at] ucl.ac.uk.</span></span> </div>
<br />
<div class="date" ></div>
   </div>
      <div class="quote">
      <!--l. 54--><p class="noindent" ><span 
class="cmbx-12">Although evidence is mounting that links global warming to changes</span>
      <span 
class="cmbx-12">in atmospheric dynamics over the Atlantic realm, similar studies</span>
      <span 
class="cmbx-12">over the African continent are lacking. And even if such models</span>
      <span 
class="cmbx-12">would  exist,  it  would  be  difficult  to  verify  their  validity  due  to</span>
      <span 
class="cmbx-12">the  paucity  of  meteorological  observations  and  anemometers  in</span>
      <span 
class="cmbx-12">the  central  Sahara.  A  pragmatic  way  around  this  problem  is  to</span>
      <span 
class="cmbx-12">monitor  barchan  dune  velocity  as  a  proxy  for  the  windiness  of</span>
      <span 
class="cmbx-12">desert areas. Dune migration rates are a measure of the amount of</span>
      <span 
class="cmbx-12">work done by the wind which does not require field measurements</span>

      <span 
class="cmbx-12">but  can  be  observed  from  space  instead.  This  paper  presents  a</span>
      <span 
class="cmbx-12">novel  application  of  the  remote  sensing  tool  COSI-Corr  for  the</span>
      <span 
class="cmbx-12">construction of time series of dune mobility from sequences of optical</span>
      <span 
class="cmbx-12">satellite imagery. The technique has been applied to the Bod</span><span 
class="cmbx-12">&eacute;l</span><span 
class="cmbx-12">&eacute;</span>
      <span 
class="cmbx-12">Depression in northern Chad, to demonstrate that dune migration</span>
      <span 
class="cmbx-12">rates in the central Sahara have been remarkably constant for nearly</span>
      <span 
class="cmbx-12">half a century, leading us to conclude that wind velocities have not</span>
      <span 
class="cmbx-12">changed more than 0.2% per year over that period. It is therefore</span>
      <span 
class="cmbx-12">unlikely that the frequency and intensity of dust storms originating</span>
      <span 
class="cmbx-12">from this &#8216;hot spot&#8217; has significantly changed over the past decades</span>
      <span 
class="cmbx-12">either.</span></div>
   <h3 class="sectionHead"><span class="titlemark">1   </span> <a 
 id="x1-10001"></a>Introduction</h3>
<!--l. 77--><p class="noindent" >As the average global temperature rises due to the greenhouse effect, the polar regions heat up
more rapidly than the low latitudes (<a href="#Xgitelman1997"><span class="cmti-12"> Gitelman et al.</span></a>, <a href="#Xgitelman1997"> 1997</a>;&nbsp;<a 
href="#Xholland2003"><span 
class="cmti-12">Holland and Bitz</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xholland2003">2003</a>). This decrease in thermal
gradient affects the dynamics of the atmosphere, leading to an overall weakening of atmospheric
circulation (<a 
href="#Xheld2006"><span 
class="cmti-12">Held and Soden</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xheld2006">2006</a>) while paradoxally increasing the storminess over the
Atlantic as well (<a 
href="#Xemanuel2005"><span 
class="cmti-12">Emanuel</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xemanuel2005">2005</a>). Much less is known about the presence or absence of large
scale trends in the windiness over the African continent, despite the important implications that
such trends might have on the global aeolian dust budget. To overcome the lack of long term
meteorological records, we propose dune migration rates as a sensitive proxy for the &#8216;effective
windiness&#8217; of desert areas, i.e., the amount of work done by the wind on the land. The
rationale is as follows. <a 
href="#Xbagnold1941"><span 
class="cmti-12">Bagnold</span></a>&#x00A0;(<a 
href="#Xbagnold1941">1941</a>) showed that the velocity (v) of barchan dunes
is inversely proportional to their height (h) and proportional to sand flux, which

in turn is approximately proportional to the cube of wind (shear) velocity (u<sub><span 
class="cmsy-8">*</span></sub>) so
that:
   <table 
class="equation"><tr><td>
   <center class="math-display" >
<img 
src="GRLpaper0x.png" alt="v = Cu3*&#x2215;h
" class="math-display" ><a 
 id="x1-1001r1"></a></center></td><td class="equation-label">(1)</td></tr></table>
<!--l. 98--><p class="nopar" >
<!--l. 100--><p class="indent" >   where C is the constant of proportionality. By taking the partial derivative of v with respect
to u<sub><span 
class="cmsy-8">*</span></sub> and rearranging, it can be shown that:
   <table 
class="equation"><tr><td>
   <center class="math-display" >
<img 
src="GRLpaper1x.png" alt="&#x2202;v     &#x2202;u *
---=  3----
 v      u*

" class="math-display" ><a 
 id="x1-1002r2"></a></center></td><td class="equation-label">(2)</td></tr></table>
<!--l. 107--><p class="nopar" >
<!--l. 109--><p class="indent" >   In other words, any change in wind velocity is &#8216;magnified&#8217; by a factor of three in the dune
velocity, or slightly less if an alternative transport equation is used instead of Equation <a 
href="#x1-1001r1">1<!--tex4ht:ref: eq:bagnold --></a>
(e.g.,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xungar1987"><span 
class="cmti-12">Ungar and Haff </span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xungar1987">1987</a>). Furthermore, the dust emission flux (f) generated by saltating
sand grains is closely proportional to sand flux as well (<a 
href="#Xshao1993"><span 
class="cmti-12">Shao et</span><span 
class="cmti-12">&#x00A0;al.</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xshao1993">1993</a>). Therefore, changes
in aeolian dust production are also governed by wind velocity according to Equation <a 
href="#x1-1002r2">2<!--tex4ht:ref: eq:rearranging --></a>
(subsituting &#8216;v&#8217; with &#8216;f&#8217;), and hence scale linearly with dune celerity. In other words, every 1%
increase in wind velocity results in a <span 
class="cmsy-10x-x-120">~</span>3% change in dune celerity and a <span 
class="cmsy-10x-x-120">~</span>3% change of dust
production as well.
<!--l. 121--><p class="noindent" >
   <h3 class="sectionHead"><span class="titlemark">2   </span> <a 
 id="x1-20002"></a>Study area</h3>
<!--l. 123--><p class="noindent" >The central Sahara contains a number of localized &#8216;hot spots&#8217; of dust production, the single
most important of which is the Bod&eacute;l&eacute; Depression of northern Chad (<a 
href="#Xgoudie2001"><span 
class="cmti-12">Goudie and</span>
<span 
class="cmti-12">Middleton</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xgoudie2001">2001</a>;&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xkoren2006"><span 
class="cmti-12">Koren et</span><span 
class="cmti-12">&#x00A0;al.</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xkoren2006">2006</a>). This 24,000km<sup><span 
class="cmr-8">2</span></sup> area supplies an estimated 6.5 million
tonnes of Fe and 0.12 million tonnes of P to the Atlantic Ocean and Amazon Basin each year
(<a 
href="#Xbristow2009"><span 
class="cmti-12">Bristow et</span><span 
class="cmti-12">&#x00A0;al.</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xbristow2009">2009</a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xbristow2010">2010</a>), due to a unique coincidence of two factors. First, the Bod&eacute;l&eacute; is
located downwind from a narrow gap between the Tibesti and Ennedi Montains on the border
with Libya, which accelerates the northeasterly trade winds to a low level jet with the capacity
to do a lot of work (<a 
href="#Xwashington2006"><span 
class="cmti-12">Washington et</span><span 
class="cmti-12">&#x00A0;al.</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xwashington2006">2006</a>). Second, it once formed the deepest part of
palaeolake Megachad which rivaled the Caspian Sea in size as recently as 8,000 years ago (<a 
href="#Xdrake2006"><span 
class="cmti-12">Drake</span>
<span 
class="cmti-12">and Bristow</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xdrake2006">2006</a>). Today, the lake has disappeared, but its sediments remain. In the Bod&eacute;l&eacute;,

these sediments form white crusts of diatomite, which is readily broken down and
transported to form some of the world&#8217;s largest and fastest barchan dunes (Figure
<a 
href="#x1-20011">1<!--tex4ht:ref: fig:locationmap --></a>).
<!--l. 141--><p class="indent" >   <hr class="figure"><div class="figure" 
>

<a 
 id="x1-20011"></a>


<!--l. 142--><p class="noindent" ><a href="fig1.png"><img 
src="fig1.png" alt="PIC" width="400"  
></a>
<br /> <div class="caption" 
><span class="id">Figure&#x00A0;1: </span><span  
class="content">Landsat-4 image (from 1984) of the eastern Bod&eacute;l&eacute; Depression with indication
of the footprints (yellow rectangles) of the other imagery used in the automated time
series analysis. Yellow shaded areas indicate areas of overlap between the seven images.</span></div><!--tex4ht:label?: x1-20011 -->

<!--l. 148--><p class="indent" >   </div><hr class="endfigure">
<!--l. 150--><p class="indent" >   We have tracked the movement of these dunes by remote sensing, using a technique called
COSI-Corr, which stands for &#8216;<span 
class="cmti-12">Co-registration of Optically Sensed Images and Correlation</span>&#8217;
(<a 
href="#Xleprince2007"><span 
class="cmti-12">Leprince et</span><span 
class="cmti-12">&#x00A0;al.</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xleprince2007">2007</a>). COSI-Corr quantifies Earth surface displacements from sub-pixel
correlations of pairs of remotely sensed optical imagery. Although the technique was originally
developed for the detection of co-seismic displacements (<a 
href="#Xavouac2006"><span 
class="cmti-12">Avouac et</span><span 
class="cmti-12">&#x00A0;al.</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xavouac2006">2006</a>), it has
since found applications in the study of glaciers, landslides, and sand dunes (<a 
href="#Xleprince2008"><span 
class="cmti-12">Leprince</span>
<span 
class="cmti-12">et</span><span 
class="cmti-12">&#x00A0;al.</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xleprince2008">2008</a>;&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xvermeesch2008b"><span 
class="cmti-12">Vermeesch and Drake</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xvermeesch2008b">2008</a>;&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xnecsoiu2009"><span 
class="cmti-12">Necsoiu et</span><span 
class="cmti-12">&#x00A0;al.</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xnecsoiu2009">2009</a>). COSI-Corr has been used to
show that the barchan dunes of the Bod&eacute;l&eacute; Depression, which are made of diatomite flakes,
are some of the fastest on the planet, with sand flux at the dune crest in excess of
200m<sup><span 
class="cmr-8">2</span></sup>yr<sup><span 
class="cmsy-8">-</span><span 
class="cmr-8">1</span></sup> (<a 
href="#Xvermeesch2008b"><span 
class="cmti-12">Vermeesch and Drake</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xvermeesch2008b">2008</a>). A 20m high barchan will therefore migrate
approximately 10m per year which is comparable to the resolution of commercial
satellite imagery available since the mid-1980s. This enables the creation of time
series of dune mobility with a temporal resolution of just a few years, allowing the
detection of temporal trends in the dune mobility, and therefore windiness, of the Bod&eacute;l&eacute;
Depression.
   <h3 class="sectionHead"><span class="titlemark">3   </span> <a 
 id="x1-30003"></a>Method</h3>
<!--l. 172--><p class="noindent" >To create such a time series, seven Landsat-4 (1984), SPOT-3 (1990 and 1996), and ASTER
(2000, 2003, 2007, and 2010) scenes were acquired from the central Bod&eacute;l&eacute; Depression (Figure
<a 
href="#x1-20011">1<!--tex4ht:ref: fig:locationmap --></a>). The images were resampled to a common resolution of 15m, georeferenced by selecting tie
points on a Landsat-7 image (band 8) from 1999, and orthorectified using an SRTM digital
elevation model. Animations of the imagery used in the time series analysis can be viewed at
<span class="obeylines-h"><span class="verb"><span 
class="cmtt-12"><a href="http://www.ucl.ac.uk/~ucfbpve/bodele">http://www.ucl.ac.uk/~ucfbpve/bodele</a></span></span></span>. Thanks to the exceptionally high sand flux in the Bod&eacute;l&eacute; Depression, aeolian processes are accelerated so that subtle trends and rare events are
magnified and multiplied. For example, detailed observations of this image sequence has
revealed several examples of shape preserving binary dune collisions (<a 
href="#Xvermeesch2011"><span class="cmti-12">Vermeesch</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xvermeesch2011">2011</a>,
<a href="http://www.ucl.ac.uk/~ucfbpve/solitons"><span class="cmtt-12">http://www.ucl.ac.uk/~ucfbpve/solitons</span></a>).
<!--l. 188--><p class="indent" >   The time series extraction algorithm comprised the following seven steps. First, dune
displacements were measured for each time step using COSI-Corr&#8217;s frequential correlator,
using a 64<span 
class="cmsy-10x-x-120">&#x00D7;</span>64 pixel correlation window (<a 
href="#Xleprince2007"><span 
class="cmti-12">Leprince et</span><span 
class="cmti-12">&#x00A0;al.</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xleprince2007">2007</a>). Second, the raw
correlation results were destriped to remove uncorrected attitude effects. Third, the
destriped displacement fields were &#8216;warped&#8217; back in time to a common reference,
namely the first image in the sequence (Figure <a 
href="#x1-30012">2<!--tex4ht:ref: fig:mapping --></a>). Fourth, the correlation results
were &#8216;cleaned&#8217; with a combination of two filters, requiring the displacements to (a)
have a high signal-to-noise ratio and (b) move in a consistent direction with time.
Fifth, the &#8216;surviving&#8217; pixels of the displacement map were connected and tracked
across the image with time, yielding a map-view of dune migration paths (Figure <a 
href="#x1-30023">3<!--tex4ht:ref: fig:dot-to-dot --></a>).
Sixth, the stepwise displacements of each dune track were projected on the resultant
migration direction (<a 
href="#Xnecsoiu2009"><span 
class="cmti-12">Necsoiu et</span><span 
class="cmti-12">&#x00A0;al.</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xnecsoiu2009">2009</a>), yielding a broad distribution of cumulative
dune displacements. Seventh, a celerity time series was created by selecting those
pixels with a total displacement near the mode of this distribution, and dividing their
stepwise displacements by the time elapsed between the satellite exposures (Figure
<a 
href="#x1-40014">4<!--tex4ht:ref: fig:timeseries --></a>).
<!--l. 209--><p class="indent" >   <hr class="figure"><div class="figure" 
>

<a 
 id="x1-30012"></a>


<!--l. 211--><p class="noindent" ><img 
src="05from06from08from09from10img_framed.png" alt="PIC"  
>
<br /> <div class="caption" 
><span class="id">Figure&#x00A0;2: </span><span  
class="content">Semi-synthetic satellite image warped back in time using the displacement
fields calculated by COSI-Corr. The &#8216;tails&#8217; attached to the dune horns are caused by the
so-called &#8216;fattening effect&#8217;, which affects features that are smaller in size than the (64<span 
class="cmsy-10x-x-120">&#x00D7;</span>64
pixel) correlation window used for the COSI-Corr analysis. This fattening effect is partly
responsible for the scatter observed in the resulting time series.</span></div><!--tex4ht:label?: x1-30012 -->

<!--l. 220--><p class="indent" >   </div><hr class="endfigure">
<!--l. 222--><p class="indent" >   The accuracy of this algorithm was demonstrated on a semi-synthetic dataset generated in
the following manner. Five repeat exposures of a large interdune area were extracted from
15m-resolution Landsat-7 images from the central Bod&eacute;l&eacute; Depression (N 16<sup><span 
class="cmsy-8">&#x2218;</span></sup>50&#8217;, E 17<sup><span 
class="cmsy-8">&#x2218;</span></sup>
50&#8217;). Then, a barchan dune was &#8216;extracted&#8217; from elsewhere in one of the images (N
16<sup><span 
class="cmsy-8">&#x2218;</span></sup>56&#8217;, E 17<sup><span 
class="cmsy-8">&#x2218;</span></sup> 05&#8217;) using a graphics editor, and superimposed on the first interdune
image. Thus, the first image in the time sequence was obtained. The second image in
the synthetic time series was generated by superimposing the same barchan dune
&#8216;clipping&#8217; on the next interdune image, with an offset of 10 pixels (150m) to the east,
and 5 pixels to the south (75m). This process was repeated for the remaining three
interdune images. The five synthetic images were subjected to the same analytical
procedure as described in the previous paragraph. Figure <a 
href="#x1-30012">2<!--tex4ht:ref: fig:mapping --></a> shows the last images
mapped back to the time of the first image, using the displacement fields calculated
by COSI-Corr. This demonstrates the effectiveness of the method used to warp the
displacement fields. Sending the raw displacements between the four time steps through the
signal-to-noise and directional filters yields a histogram with total displacements of
669<span 
class="cmsy-10x-x-120">&plusmn;</span>23m (2<span 
class="cmmi-12">&#x03C3;</span>), which is in good agreement with the known displacement of 668m (=
4 <span 
class="cmsy-10x-x-120">&#x00D7;</span><img
src="GRLpaper2x.png" alt="&#x221A; -----------
  1502 + 752"  class="sqrt" >).
<!--l. 245--><p class="indent" >   <hr class="figure"><div class="figure" 
>

<a 
 id="x1-30023"></a>


<!--l. 246--><p class="noindent" ><a href="fig3.png"><img 
src="fig3.png" alt="PIC"  width="400"
></a>
<br /> <div class="caption" 
><span class="id">Figure&#x00A0;3: </span><span  
class="content">Map-view of individually tracked image pixels of sand dunes in the central
Bod&eacute;l&eacute;  Depression.  Black  lines  and  coloured  dots  were  produced  by  the  automated
COSI-Corr algorithm. Grey crescents mark the footprints of the corresponding barchan
dunes in an analog Corona (KH-4) declassified American spy satellite image.</span></div><!--tex4ht:label?: x1-30023 -->

<!--l. 253--><p class="indent" >   </div><hr class="endfigure">
   <h3 class="sectionHead"><span class="titlemark">4   </span> <a 
 id="x1-40004"></a>Results</h3>
<!--l. 257--><p class="noindent" >Applying the time series extraction algorithm to our sequence of seven coregistered images from
the Bod&eacute;l&eacute; Depression yielded 2853 individually tracked pixels with raw dune celerities between
0 and 50m yr<sup><span 
class="cmsy-8">-</span><span 
class="cmr-8">1</span></sup> and a broad distribution of total displacements with a mode at <span 
class="cmsy-10x-x-120">~</span>600m. The
automated analysis was extended further back into the past by comparison of the
1984 image with declassified American spy satellite (Corona) images from 1965 and
1970. Due to the presence of specks of dust as well as image distortions caused by
shrinking of the photographic film, it was not possible to automatically measure the dune
displacements of these scenes with COSI-Corr. Instead, the image was georeferenced and
coregistered to the 1984 Landsat imagery by third order polynomial fits to 531 tie
points, and the displacements of ten large barchan dunes were measured by hand.
Thanks to the 19-year time lapse between the two images used for these &#8216;analog&#8217;
measurements, their precision is better than 5%, which is comparable with that of the
automated COSI-Corr analysis. The resulting dune celerities are identical to the
automated measurements, which themselves show less than 10% temporal variability
over the subsequent 26 years (Figure <a 
href="#x1-40014">4<!--tex4ht:ref: fig:timeseries --></a>). The lack of any trend in the time series of
dune celerity paints a picture of remarkably stable dune mobility over the past 45
years.
<!--l. 279--><p class="indent" >   <hr class="figure"><div class="figure" 
>

<a 
 id="x1-40014"></a>


<!--l. 280--><p class="noindent" ><a href="fig4.png"><img 
src="fig4.png" alt="PIC"  width="400"
></a>
<br /> <div class="caption" 
><span class="id">Figure&#x00A0;4: </span><span  
class="content">Normalised time series of dune mobility for the Bod&eacute;l&eacute; data set, based on 2583
dune displacements with a total displacement of 600<span 
class="cmsy-10x-x-120">&plusmn;</span>100m. The red contours mark the
precentiles of the observed distribution, with the darkest shade of red corresponding to the
median. The dashed lines show the migration rates of ten dunes tracked by hand between
a 1967 Corona spy satellity image and a Landsat image from 1984. White lines mark a
linear least squares regression of the mean celerities and its 95% confidence envelope. The
lack of any trend in the time series indicates that the &#8216;effective storminess&#8217; of the Sahara
has remained constant over the past 45 years.</span></div><!--tex4ht:label?: x1-40014 -->

<!--l. 293--><p class="indent" >   </div><hr class="endfigure">
   <h3 class="sectionHead"><span class="titlemark">5   </span> <a 
 id="x1-50005"></a>Discussion</h3>
<!--l. 297--><p class="noindent" >Previous studies (<a 
href="#Xprospero2003"><span 
class="cmti-12">Prospero and Lamb</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xprospero2003">2003</a>;&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xmukhopadhyay2008"><span 
class="cmti-12">Mukhopadhyay and Kreycik</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xmukhopadhyay2008">2008</a>) have indicated
that the dust output of the Sahara has undergone significant variations over the course of the
past few decades, with relatively low dust levels during the 1960s, high dust production during
the 1970s and 1980s, and a gradual decrease after that. These changes can be explained either
by (a) changes in precipitation and vegetation cover (<a 
href="#Xmiddleton1985"><span 
class="cmti-12">Middleton</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xmiddleton1985">1985</a>;&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xschlesinger1990"><span 
class="cmti-12">Schlesinger</span>
<span 
class="cmti-12">et</span><span 
class="cmti-12">&#x00A0;al.</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xschlesinger1990">1990</a>;&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xnicholson1998"><span 
class="cmti-12">Nicholson et</span><span 
class="cmti-12">&#x00A0;al.</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xnicholson1998">1998</a>), or (b) changes in the wind regime and storminess of the
desert (<a 
href="#Xruddiman1997"><span 
class="cmti-12">Ruddiman</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xruddiman1997">1997</a>;&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xgillette1999"><span 
class="cmti-12">Gillette</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xgillette1999">1999</a>;&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xgoudie2001"><span 
class="cmti-12">Goudie and Middleton</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xgoudie2001">2001</a>;&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xbozzano2002"><span 
class="cmti-12">Bozzano</span>
<span 
class="cmti-12">et</span><span 
class="cmti-12">&#x00A0;al.</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xbozzano2002">2002</a>;&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xprospero2003"><span 
class="cmti-12">Prospero and Lamb</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xprospero2003">2003</a>). Whereas the first model has been validated by remote
sensing (<a 
href="#Xtucker1991"><span 
class="cmti-12">Tucker et</span><span 
class="cmti-12">&#x00A0;al.</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xtucker1991">1991</a>;&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xnicholson1998"><span 
class="cmti-12">Nicholson et</span><span 
class="cmti-12">&#x00A0;al.</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xnicholson1998">1998</a>), the second model is much harder to test.
In a recent study, <span 
class="cmbx-12">? </span>used a 23-year record of GEOSAT altimeter data to reconstruct
trends in wind speed over the oceanic realm. For the north Atlantic, they found an
increasing trend of 0-1% per year. As discussed before, no such data are available over
the African continent, and herein lies the value of our dune celerity time series. A
95% confidence envelope for a linear least squares regression of our dataset indicates
that dune velocities have changed less than 10% over the 26 year duration of the
automated analysis, corresponding to an annual change of less than 0.4% per year. Using
Equation <a 
href="#x1-1002r2">2<!--tex4ht:ref: eq:rearranging --></a>, this translates into an annual change of the wind velocity of probably less
than 0.13% and (accounting for different transport equations) certainly less than
0.2%.
<!--l. 322--><p class="indent" >   As briefly discussed in Section <a 
href="#x1-10001">1<!--tex4ht:ref: sec:intro --></a>, wind tunnel experiments have shown that the
emission flux of aeolian dust is proportional to the saltation flux of aeolian sand

(<a 
href="#Xshao1993"><span 
class="cmti-12">Shao et</span><span 
class="cmti-12">&#x00A0;al.</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xshao1993">1993</a>;&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xshao2009"><span 
class="cmti-12">Shao</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xshao2009">2009</a>), which in turn is proportional to dune velocity. There
should therefore exist a correlation between dust production and dune mobility in
the area. The constance of dune mobility in the 45-year time series of the Bod&eacute;l&eacute;
dunes indicates that the &#8216;effective windiness&#8217; of the so-called &#8216;Bod&eacute;l&eacute; Low Level Jet&#8217;
(<a 
href="#Xwashington2006"><span 
class="cmti-12">Washington et</span><span 
class="cmti-12">&#x00A0;al.</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xwashington2006">2006</a>;&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xwarren2007"><span 
class="cmti-12">Warren et</span><span 
class="cmti-12">&#x00A0;al.</span></a>,&#x00A0;<a 
href="#Xwarren2007">2007</a>) has not significantly changed over the past
half century, and it is therefore unlikely that the frequency and intensity of aeolian
dust storms originating from this important area has significantly changed over that
time period either. In conclusion, we have found no evidence that (anthropogenic)
climate change has significantly affected atmospheric circulation over the central
Sahara.
